Aug 26 2007 	Loved the spacioussolid rooms but there are some problems	We visited the Westland hotel from 21 – 24 August 2007. It is just what you expect from an old English hotel: a large lobby, well decorated in an “old-fashioned” style and very kind staff. We booked a single and a double room. The former was a rather small room at the rear of the hotel, the latter was a spacious room on the 5th floor with a wide view on Kensington Gardens. Westland is situated on the very busy Bayswater road, but the double glazed windows tempered the traffic noise, although this will probably not be sufficient on the first three floors. There are several bus stops in front of the hotel and the underground is about 300 meters away. This means that there is a direct connection with the city centre and the Royal Albert Hall as well (bus 70). There is a very nice bar, the Black Lions, near the corner of Bayswater Road and Queensway, where you can have a good meal and nice wine at reasonable prices. The Bar Churchill Arms is worth the visit too (take the bus in the direction of the Albert Hall). There are several good restaurants in the neighbourhood. There is no air-conditioning, so during warm periods it might be rather unpleasant, certainly if you let the street noise prevent you from opening a window. This wasn’t our problem at all, as the weather was rather rainy. The rooms are carpeted and well decorated and have a trouser press, an ironing board, a desk, a linen cupboard, a TV (only 5 channels) + radio and coffee/tea facilities (but without the usual coffee- or teabags). Our beds had very good mattresses and blankets that smelled a little dusty (which was no problem after I beat my blankets after the first night). There is a large bathroom with a hair dryer, a tub and a shower, but showering is a problem. In the single room it was impossible to take a shower in the morning: if the tap is coming above point 3 on a 10 points scale, there is no hot water. In the double room the water pressure varies from a small jet to normal. In this bathroom the ventilator works night and day, and you cannot switch it off. We informed the staff, but no action was taken. Continental breakfast was included in the price of the room and consisted of juice, toasted bread, butter, jam/marmalade and tea or coffee. For an additional 8 pounds (about 12 euro) it is possible of having a full English breakfast. Then you can also have cornflakes, eggs, bacon, sausage and porridge or kippers or baked beans or cheese and hot chocolate. For this price, I have had better breakfasts. We booked through Buro Britan in Amsterdam and paid 525,00 euro for both rooms, which is really a good offer. Will we return at that price? Probably yes, but only when we can have a room far from Bayswater road.	
Jul 3 2007 	Very large rooms for a reasonable price	The Westland Hotel offers very large rooms for a reasonable price by London standards. The hotel is well situated near the northwest corner of Kensington Park and is close to 2 Circle line tube stops. The front desk staff is very helpful and there are plenty of good restaurants nearby. Rooms are kept quite clean though the decor is not fancy (we had a standard room) but who cares about room decor as you're there to see London! The shower is strong and has plenty of hot water excpet in the early morning hours. Unlike many other places we stayed in England there is actually a large tub in the spacious bathroom if you prefer baths to showers. English breakfast is included in the price of the room and it's quite good with fast service if you're in a hurry to get our sightseeing.	
